text.tspan: In the aftermath of the leftist Carnation Revolution, Portuguese settlers in Mozambique were
worried about their fate. Many Portuguese settlers in Mozambique feared that if Mozambique
was placed under majority-rule, they would have their property siezed, and possibly be subject to
violence at the hands of rebel groups like FRELIMO. In September of 1974, the Portuguese
Government announced that Mozambique would be granted Independence under majority rule,
with FRELIMO heading up the new government. Fearing the worst, the Portuguese Settlers
decided to take control of Mozambique for themselves. In Lourenço Marques, several Portugese
Settlers took over a radio station, and proclaimed the establishment of the Laurentian Republic.
Portuguese settlers across Mozambique systematically took control of nearly 2/3rds of the country,
including all of the major population centers, within a week of this declaration. The Portuguese
Military did nothing to stop the settler´s seizure of control, and in many cases, actively assisted the
settlers. The Portuguese government in Lisbon, uneager to be reinvolved in the War, ordered the
Military to withdraw from Mozambique, leaving most of the country under the undisputed control
of the settlers. The Laurentian Republic´s intial success would prove short lived. FRELIMO, now
without the worry of combating the Portuguese Military, launched their own version of the Tet
Offensive throughout Mozambique. Much of the countryside fell quickly to FRELIMO, along
with major cities in Northern Mozambique. After Nampula was captured by FRELIMO, the
People´s Republic of Mozambique was formally established. The People´s Republic of
Mozambique soon launched an offensive to capture the southern half of Mozambique. The rebels
rapidly made ground, any by the time they had reached the outskirts of Lourenço Marques, most
of the southern half of Mozambique was in rebel hands, with the notable exception of Beira, which
continued to remain as a settler holdout. While it appeared the Laurentian Republic was doomed,
outside forces would conspire to ensure the nation survived. South Africa, and Rhodesia, fearing
that Mozambique would be used as bases for rebel groups trying to take over their countries,
decided to launch a Military intervention in favor of the Laurentian Republic. The Army of the
People´s Republic of Mozambique proved no match for the modern South African and Rhodesian
militaries. While the southern half of Mozambique was easily reincorporated into the Laurentian
Republic, the northern half of the country proved more difficult to pacify. Ultimately, the South
African and Rhodesian militaries decided to retreat south of the Zambeze and Chire rivers, leaving
the Lauretnian Republic in control of the southern half of the country. Across the Zambeze and
Chire rivers, the South African and Rhodeisan military helped prop up the western-friendly
Republic of Rombezia under the control of RENAMO, before retreating south. The Republic of
Rombezia managed to take control of the former Zambezia province, but failed to take over
anymore of the northern half of Mozambique. At the present day, the People´s Republic of
Mozambique claims the lands of Laurentia and Rombezia as its own, while the Republic of
Rombezia claims the land of the People´s Republic of Mozambique as its own.
